Rating: 4
Pancakes only - amazing! No changes. Instead of mashing the potato, put all in a glass bowl and used hand held electric mixer to reduce all that solid to a batter. Pan cakes were a lovely pinkish/orangeish color, and light and fluffy. The cakes could make a snack alone, or a wrap or fold to contain cream cheese and jams etc.

Rating: 2
I would rate these better if it were not for the texture. They were very delicate so make them small. Mine were too spongy and wet even after overcooking. I'm thinking my sweet potato was very moist or I needed to add more pancake mix - perhaps a sturdier kind with whole grain to give more structure to the pancake. Anybody else have that problem? And how did you solve it - they are tasty so I'd like to play around with it until it comes out good.

Rating: 4
Excellent recipe! I had some left over sweet potato mash that this was perfect for. I skipped on the buttermilk and went with 1-1/2 cups soy milk with a full 2 cups of sweet potato mash and it still came out delicious. One recommendation I have is to make small cakes with this. The batter is thick and heavy so it is difficult to flip a big pancake. Enjoy!

